name: D-amino acid dehydrogenase (quinone)
classes: Acting on the CH-NH2 group of donors;
With a quinone or other compound as acceptor
reaction: a D-amino acid + H2O + a quinone = a 2-oxo carboxylate + NH3 + a quinol [RN:R09493]
comment: An iron-sulfur flavoprotein (FAD). The enzyme from the bacterium Helicobacter pylori is highly specific for D-proline, while the enzyme from the bacterium Escherichia coli B is most active with D-alanine, D-phenylalanine and D-methionine. This enzyme may be the same as EC 1.4.99.6.

references.title: Purification and properties of D-amino acid dehydrogenase, an inducible membrane-bound iron-sulfur flavoenzyme from Escherichia coli B.
D-Amino acid dehydrogenase from Helicobacter pylori NCTC 11637.
